      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prime-Time Politics, Ready or Not</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lee Bergman letter on Sept 9 editorial agrees Sen Joseph I Lieberman should resign from Senate race in Connecticut; notes Gore-Lieberman victory would enable Gov John G Rowland to name Republican as Lieberman's Senate successor</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You are right that Senator Joseph I. Lieberman should resign from the Senate race in Connecticut (editorial, Sept. 9). Should the Gore-Lieberman ticket win, the possibility of a Democratic majority in the Senate would be weakened greatly when the ensuing senatorial vacancy is filled by Gov. John G. Rowland of Connecticut, a Republican.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You are right that Senator Joseph I. Lieberman should resign from the Senate race in Connecticut (editorial, Sept. 9). Should the Gore-Lieberman ticket win, the possibility of a Democratic majority in the Senate would be weakened greatly when the ensuing senatorial vacancy is filled by Gov. John G. Rowland of Connecticut, a Republican.</p>
        <p>If Mr. Lieberman hopes to keep his credibility intact, he can't have it both ways. He must drop out now,  allowing another Democrat to replace him on the ballot.</p>
        <p>LEE BERGMAN  Tuckahoe, N.Y., Sept. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
